Important Linux Documentation Sources
======================================
The man pages (short for manual pages)
GNU info
The help command and --help option
Other Documentation sources http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en

Man
===

man -f commandName gives brief description of what command will do that.
whatis commandName gives brief description of what command will do that.

man -k commandName gives the list of possible commands with the commandName part of it.
apropos commandName gives the list of possible commands with the commandName part of it.

The man pages are divided into nine numbered chapters (chap 1 to chap 9)

man chapterNumber commandName gives that chapterNumber of that command Name
man -a commandName giveslist of all chapters available in all manual pages where the command Name is used

The GNU info System
===================
GNU info system resembles man in many ways. The topics in info are connected are using links.
Information can be viewed through either a command line interface, a graphical help utility, printed or viewed online.

Introduction to help option
============================
man --help option is useful as quick reference and it displays information faster than the man and info pages.

it is the best way to see the what are the possible options for the given command.
y
gnome-help will provide graphical desktop help mode

some of the help pages are available as part of /usr/share/doc directory, the information that we get is package information

Summary
=======

The main source of linux documentation are the man pages, GNU info page, the help options and command and a rich variety of online documentation sources.

The man utility searches, formats and displays man pages.

The man pages provide in-depth documentation about programs and other topics about the system including configuration files, system calls, library calls and routines.

The GNU Info system was created by GNU project as its standard documentation. It is robust and is accessible via command line, web and graphical tools using info

short descriptions for commands are usually displayed with -h or --help argument.

you can type help at the command line to display a synopsis of built in commands 

